    2026-05-18T13:00:00Z)

(Decision
    "Intent files use lock-free append semantics. Concurrent agents recording intent `>>` to the topic file without coordination — POSIX O_APPEND atomicity for writes under PIPE_BUF (4096 bytes on Linux) means concurrent small appends sequence cleanly without mangling. Each intent record stays well under 4KB. File format dropped the outer `[ … ]` wrapping so naive append works; intent files are now a sequence of top-level NOTA records."
    "Wouldn't it be possible to use a shell call to append something in an intent file so that essentially there's no need to lock it? Because if two append calls come in through Linux, correct me if I'm wrong, but they're not going to actually mangle the text together. They're just going to come in in sequence, right?"
    "Psyche's intuition about Linux atomic-append is correct. Triggered the format change (drop outer brackets) so `cat >> file <<EOF` works without locking. This entry was itself appended via that mechanism — meta-witness."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19T16:05:00Z)

(Correction
    "Don't claim a lock for an intent-append. Use `cat >> intent/<topic>.nota <<'EOF' … EOF` (or any shell append). Locks are for supersession edits (rewriting prior records); recording new intent is lock-free."
    "So if I'm right in what I'm saying, I guess you locking the file to edit it means that I'm wrong, otherwise you would have used a shellcall to append what you wanted to add in there instead of trying to acquire a lock for it. So by your actions either you're saying I'm wrong or you didn't actually understand and process what I said."
    "Catching the contradiction: I claimed the lock and used Edit instead of demonstrating the shell append, despite the psyche's intuition being correct. Reordering: lock-free `>>` for new records; lock only for rewrites."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19T16:05:00Z)

(Decision
    "Document the lock-free-append exemption in the orchestrate protocol. Routine intent recording (appending a record to intent/<topic>.nota) is exempt from the claim flow — same status as reports, which each role writes to its own subdir without claiming. Topic file does not have to exist; `>>` creates it. Only supersession edits / rewrites need locks."
    "You should also edit the orchestrate protocol, the orchestrate skill, to specify how to, how if an intent already has a topic file, that, well, even if there isn't one, right, like, because if you append to a file that doesn't exist, it's going to create the file, unless I'm wrong, that you can just do this without claiming a lock."
    "Psyche extending the lock-free-append discipline into orchestrate/AGENTS.md so all peer agents see it. File creation via `>>` is also lock-free (open(O_CREAT|O_APPEND) is atomic per POSIX)."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19T16:20:00Z)

